<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-124-038  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 124 038.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Feb 6 1990 v4 n5 p14(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;ne</JOURNAL><TITLE>Catspaw tosses SPITBOL to Mac. (SPITBOL and Icon programminglanguages) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Said, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Catspaw Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   MaxSPITBOL (Program development software) (product introduction)Pro*Icon (Compiler) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Programming LanguagesImplementationProduct IntroductionCompilers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Carolyn SaidandM;Salida, Colo.andP;  -- Maybe classic programming languages never die, they justget ported to the Mac.andM;Catspaw Inc. late last year released versions of SPITBOL and Icon, twolanguages popular in public-domain releases from the 1960s and '70s that havebeen updated with multiple windows, pull-down menus and mouse access.andM;andgt;MaxSPITBOL is a $195 implementation of a language known for its strongtext-handling abilities.andP;  It is upwardly compatible with Bell Laboratories'SNOBOL4 programming language.andP;  SPITBOL is a faster derivative of SNOBOL.andM;&quot;MaxSPITBOL is by far the best implementation of SNOBOL I've seen.andP;  The userinterface is superb,&quot; said Marc Rochkind, president of Advanced ProgrammingInstitute in Boulder, Colo.andM;Rochkind said he used MaxSPIT-BOL to generate documentation, convert a PCLotus Agenda file to Microsoft Word on the Mac and to do database publishing.andM;The language offers powerful string-matching capabilities, many high-leveloperators and a sophisticated use of memory, Rochkind said.andM;andgt;Pro*Icon is a $175 implementation of Icon, a general-purpose language usedfor text processing, rapid prototyping, artificial intelligence and expertsystems.andM;The language's strengths include automatic storage management, an extensiverepertoire of string operations, and sophisticated data structures such assets and tables with associative look-up, according to Catspaw.andM;&quot;People's eyes light up when they talk about these languages,&quot; said MarkEmmer, Catspaw's president.andP;  &quot;You can craft neat, jewel-like solutions withthem.&quot;andM;Both languages were created by Ralph Griswold, a noted computer scientist nowat the University of Arizona in Tucson.andP;  Both offer power and ease of use,Emmer said.andP;  Icon, developed in the 1970s, incorporates mathematicalexpressions, goal-directed evaluation and complex string scanning.andP;  SNOBOL, aproduct of the 1960s, is more pattern-oriented, in that it recognizes variousfeatures in a text string, he said.andM;Catspaw Inc. can be reached at P.O.andP;  Box 1123, Salida, Colo.andP;  81201; (719)539-3884.andP;  n</TEXT></DOC>